s developed, and continue to develop, their own formal immigration strategies and implement various selections and integration policies. This book argues that the process of federalization is largely the result of provincial mobilization. In each province, mobilization occurred through a modern iteration of province building, this time focused on immigrants as resources for provincial economies and societies. Advocating for a province-centred analysis of federalism, Province Building and the Federalization of Immigration in Canada provides key lessons to understanding the contemporary governance of immigration in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh  afederalism.  ahistorical institutionalism.  aimmigrant integration.  aimmigration.  aintergovernmental relations.  aprovincial politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751309240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487513092423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487513092.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles